message.content: First we could write $216$ and $\sqrt{6}$ both with base $\sqrt{6}$.  We have $216=(\sqrt{6})^3$, so now our expression has a base of $\sqrt{6}$.  The expression $\log_{\sqrt{6}}(\sqrt{6})$ equals $1$, because the $\log_b b =1$ for all $b\neq 1$.  Hence, $\log_{\sqrt{6}}(216\sqrt{6}) = \log_{\sqrt{6}}( (\sqrt{6})^3 (\sqrt{6}) ) = \log_{\sqrt{6}}((\sqrt{6})^4)$.  Since $\log_a (a^n) = n$, this equals $4$, so $\log_{\sqrt{6}} (216\sqrt{6}) = \boxed{4}$.
